	url = {https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2021AJ....161...69K},
	doi = {10.3847/1538-3881/abd2c1},
	abstract = {We present a framework for estimating exoplanet occurrence rates by synthesizing constraints from radial velocity and transit surveys simultaneously. We employ approximate Bayesian computation and various mass-radius (M-R) relations to explore the population models describing these surveys, both separately and in a joint fit. Using this approach, we fit a planet distribution function of the form \$\{d\}{\textasciicircum}\{2\}N/d{\textbackslash}mathrm\{log\}\{Pd\}{\textbackslash}mathrm\{log\}M{\textbackslash}propto \{P\}{\textasciicircum}\{{\textbackslash}beta \}\{M\}{\textasciicircum}\{{\textbackslash}alpha \}\$ , with a break in the power law in mass at Mb, to planets orbiting FGK stars with periods \$P=[25,200]\$ days and masses \$M=[2,50]\{M\}\_\{{\textbackslash}oplus \}\$ . We find that the M-R relation from Otegi et al. (2020), which lets rocky and volatile-rich populations overlap in mass, allows us to find a model that is consistent with both types of surveys. Our joint fit gives \$\{M\}\_\{b\}=\{21.6\}\_\{-3.2\}{\textasciicircum}\{+2.5\}\{M\}\_\{{\textbackslash}oplus \}\$ (errors reflect 68.3\% credible interval). This is nearly a factor of three higher than the break from transit-only considerations and an M-R relation without such an overlap. The corresponding planet-star mass ratio break \$\{q\}\_\{b\}{\textbackslash}sim 7{\textbackslash}times \{10\}{\textasciicircum}\{-5\}\$ may be consistent with microlensing studies ( \$\{q\}\_\{b\}{\textbackslash}sim 6{\textbackslash}times \{10\}{\textasciicircum}\{-5\}-2{\textbackslash}times \{10\}{\textasciicircum}\{-4\}\$ ). The joint fit also requires that a fraction of \$\{F\}\_\{{\textbackslash}mathrm\{rocky\}\}=\{0.63\}\_\{-0.04\}{\textasciicircum}\{+0.04\}\$ planets in the overlap region belong to the rocky population. Our results strongly suggest that future M-R relations should account for a mixture of distinct types of planets in order to describe the observed planet population.},
